# Audit Result: PASS

No blocking issues. The WMS main product chain changes, browser coverage, and risk surface all check out against the current code and the diff under review.

## 1. WMS main product chain — PASS

**Manual inbound creates/reuses SubProject** — `backend/src/modules/wms/service.ts:441-453`
The new `createManualInbound` resolves `subProjectId` via `findFirst({ where: { tenantId, departmentId, name: firstProjectName, isActive: true } })` and falls back to `subProject.create({ data: { ..., name: firstProjectName, code: null, description: '由手动入库项目名称自动创建' } })`. The created SubProject then drives inventory keying at line 482. The same name on later inbound reuses the row. The Returns page can subsequently select it via `wmsApi.getSubProjects()` (`frontend/src/pages/wms/Returns.tsx:135-141`). No race because the lookup + create run inside the same `prisma.$transaction` block (line 423).

**Outbound preserves work-team information** — `service.ts:1037-1049`
`workTeam` is resolved with `tx.workTeam.findUnique({ where: { id: data.workTeamId } })` before the create, and the new diff writes `workTeamName: workTeam?.name || null` to the `OutboundOrder`. `OutboundOrder.workTeamName` is `String?` in the schema (`backend/prisma/schema.prisma:619`), so the write is valid. The work-team ledger then reads `item.outboundOrder.workTeamName` (`service.ts:1529`) to populate `workTeamName` in the flat shape.

**Returns no longer write fields absent on `ReturnItem`** — `service.ts:1235-1241` and `1270-1272`
Verified against schema (`schema.prisma:684-695`): `ReturnItem` has only `id, returnOrderId, outboundItemId, materialId, quantity, material, outboundItem, returnOrder`. The diff correctly drops `projectName`, `unitPrice`, and `unit`. The Excel return path is also cleaned.

**Work-team ledger returns the flat shape and supports keyword filtering** — `service.ts:1515-1554`
The shape now emits `id, workTeamName, materialName, unit, quantity, unitPrice, totalAmount, outboundDate, projectName, type, returnedQuantity`. Cross-checked against `frontend/src/pages/wms/Ledger.tsx:14-21, 104-109` — every field the frontend reads (`workTeamName, projectName, materialName, unitPrice`) is present. Keyword filter is `materialName + workTeamName + projectName` case-insensitive substring. The new `keyword` query param is wired through `backend/src/modules/wms/routes.ts:1237`.

## 2. Browser coverage realism — PASS

`frontend/tests/smoke/browser-smoke.spec.ts:545-643` runs a real end-to-end chain on system Google Chrome (`frontend/playwright.config.ts:33`: `channel: 'chrome'`, not headless fake). The test:

- **Real UI** (not API mocking): opens each page, clicks real buttons (`新增入库`, `新增出库`, `新增退库`, `新增调拨`, `返回继续出库`), types into real inputs (`输入供应商名称`, `输入物资名称`, `单位`, `项目名称`, `数量`, `实收`, `单价`), interacts with real modals (`chooseMultiSelectModalOption`, `chooseSingleSelectModalOption`, `selectFirstRealOption`).
- **Inbound creates inbound** and confirms a new row appears in the table (`tr', { hasText: supplierName }`), then opens the detail dialog and verifies the material row.
- **Outbound** opens a department modal, checks the material appears in inventory, selects a work team from a real `<select>`, fills the quantity, clicks `确认出库`, and asserts the success heading `出库成功`.
- **Outbound PDF download** — `page.waitForEvent('download')` is the right way to verify a real PDF download (not a route open). Filename asserted to match `/^出库单-.*\.pdf$/`.
- **Return** picks the SubProject that was auto-created during inbound (the same `projectName` the test passed into the inbound form), queries the outbound item, and confirms the return.
- **Transfer** exercises both department modals (`选择调出项目部`, `选择调入项目部`) and the transfer PDF download.
- **Ledger** searches by the new keyword filter and confirms the material row.

Confirmed in `docs/smoke-evidence/playwright-results.json`: 9/9 suites pass, including `enterprise user can complete wms inbound outbound return transfer chain: ok=True`. New screenshot saved at `docs/smoke-evidence/物资主链路CRUD.png`.

## 3. Risks — PASS

**Tenant isolation** — all changed code paths continue to use `data.tenantId` as the discriminator. `createManualInbound` adds SubProject keyed by `tenantId` (line 446). `createOutbound` ledger reads still gated on `outboundOrder: { tenantId }` (line 1507). The flat-shape rewrite preserves this filter (line 1507). No cross-tenant data exposure introduced.

**Module entitlement boundaries** — the new ledger endpoint adds `keyword` to the existing `requirePermission('canViewWorkTeamLedger')` route (`routes.ts:1234-1241`); the permission check is unchanged. No new endpoint added that bypasses `requirePermission` or `requireModuleAccess`.

**Inventory accounting regressions** — the diff only changes how `subProjectId` is derived for inbound (line 441-453) and consistently uses the same `resolvedSubProjectId` for both the `InboundOrder` and the inventory `findFirst`/`create` (lines 458, 482). The inventory key `[subProjectId, materialId, projectName]` is preserved. Outbound `spId` was not changed. Return flow does not touch inventory math — it only cleans the `ReturnItem` create payload.

**Data-loss / destructive behavior** — the diff is additive to `createManualInbound` and `createOutbound`, and reductive to `createReturn`/`createExcelReturn` (removes writes of fields that don't exist, so no rows are deleted; previously these would have errored at Prisma level and crashed the whole create). The ledger function switches from `prisma.outboundItem.findMany` + page in SQL to fetch-all + slice in JS (line 1518-1552), which is a small perf trade-off but not destructive.

**Public repo secret leakage** — no secrets in the diff. Test data uses `Date.now()` stamps as test isolation. No API keys, tokens, or real credentials.

## Minor observations (non-blocking)

- `service.ts:445-450` creates the SubProject without a `code` (code is nullable per schema), so the `@@unique([tenantId, departmentId, code])` index allows multiple nulls and the same `name` can coexist with prior rows. Naming is not enforced unique — acceptable for the auto-create path but worth noting if a future reviewer expects strict uniqueness.
- The new `listWorkTeamLedger` loads all matching items, computes `returnedQuantity` for each, then slices for pagination (lines 1518-1552). For tenants with very large outbound history this is O(N) per request instead of DB-paginated. Acceptable for current scale; flag if data volume grows.
- The transfer test does not assert tenant isolation or module-entitlement boundaries directly — those are covered by the existing 9-test matrix.

`PASS` — no blockers. The 9/9 real-Chrome smoke run plus the schema-cross-checked source diff cover the audit scope.
